HEADWORD: Delicatessen
<hw>Del`i*ca*tes"sen</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[G., fr.
F. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧licatesse</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Relishes for
the table; dainties; delicacies.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A dealer in
<xex>delicatessen</xex>⟦rdquo⟧. <rj><au>G. H. Putnam.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>ready-to-eat foods, such as cold cuts, cooked meats,
and prepared salads.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <singf>sing.</singf>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>delicatessens</plw>.</plu> <def>a store or section of a store where
delicatessen{2} is sold.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Get a sandwich for lunch at the
<ex>delicatessen</ex> counter.⟦rdquo⟧⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

